"{\"uid\": \"rollingstone.com-music-music-news-snoop-dogg-named-olympic-flame-torchbearer-1235065827\", \"text\": \"ByLarisha Paul  TheParisOlympicsare heating up. Thetorch relaythrough France is already underway, currently passing through Yvelines into Hauts-de-Seine. After those territories have been covered, the second to last stretch of the journey before the opening ceremony will begin tomorrow, withSnoop Doggserving as torchbearer for the Saint-Denis portion of the relay.  The rapper joins the hundreds of torchbearers who have assisted in the Olympic flame's journey across France, which began on May 8. Saint-Denis is part of stage 67 on the route to Paris. The stage begins in Quartier Pleyel before moving through Village Olympique into Saint-Denis. From there, it moves to Canal Saint-Denis into Parc de le Villette-Club France, Canal Saint-Martin, and Concert Basilique de Saint-Denis. After that, its next stop is the Olympic Cauldron.Trending StoriesJohn Lithgow Knows J.K. Rowling's Anti-Trans Views Will Now Forever Come Up in 'Every Interview'Kevin Spacey's 'Mental Illness' Should Trigger $29.5 Million Payout, 'House of Cards' Trial Jurors HearBTS Nails Its Comeback With 'Arirang'Top Disaster Response Official Claims He Teleported to a Waffle House  The final torchbearer who will close out the weeks-long Olympic relay journey has yet to be revealed, but they have some big shoes to fill. Snoop has been an unwavering team player since beginning his stint as a guest commentator at the 2024 Paris games. When the games officially kick off on July 26, the rapper will be the go-to source for special reports for the Olympics primetime show on NBC and Peacock. Last month, hemade an appearanceduring Team USA's track and field trials and completed the mock 200-meter dash in 34.44 seconds.  Snoop will be attending Olympic events, stopping in at trademarks throughout Paris, and catching up with competing athletes, as well as the friends and family members cheering them on. Hisplay-by-playabout a crip-walking horse from the equestrian event at the 2021 Tokyo games is what landed him the commentator gig in the first place. \\\"I am going to meet the horse in real life. He's the returning champ,\\\" the rapper saidearlier this year.\\\"So I got to go meet him - you know what I am saying? - and let him know I am a big fan.\\\"  We want to hear it. Send us a tip using our anonymous form.  Rolling Stone is a part of Penske Media Corporation. \\u00a9 2026 Rolling Stone, LLC. All rights reserved.\"}"